,"1180":"1180","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1225–1298":"about 1225–1298","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1250–1330":"1250–1330","–1272":"–1272","1180–1250":"1180–1250","Abt 1272":"about 1272","1225":"1225","1298":"1298","1330":"1330","Aft 1250":"after 1250","Abt 1225":"about 1225","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","Perth, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Ruthven of Ruthven was born about 1225, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Walter de Ruthven and Cecilia Strathearn. He had at least 